\begin_layout Standard
La conclusion ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Interest Rate Derivatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color red
Work on this topic must focus on the end result: pricing of bonds, caps
 and oors (working and pricing vanilla and Bermudan swaptions is an extra),
 as opposed to the calibration of HJM or BGM (LMM) model per se.
 Both models impose the no-arbitrage restriction: the drift cannot be random
 and depends on volatility of forward rates.
 The distinction is how this key input is estimated: from interest rates
 data (historic) or market instruments (forward-looking).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model, hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Pricincipal component analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Heath–Jarrow–Morton
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instantenuous forward rate f(t,T), as seen from time t, starts at time T
 and applies over an instant 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a number from a continusous proces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f(t,T) & = & -\lim_{\varDelta t\rightarrow0}\frac{\log Z(t;T+\varDelta t)-\log Z(t;T)}{\varDelta t}\\
 & = & -\frac{\partial}{\partial T}\;\log\; Z(t;T)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, the N-dimensional SDE (multi-factor HJM) is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
df(t,T)=m(t,T)dt+\sum_{i=1}^{N}\nu_{i}(t,T)dX_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with the risk-neutral drift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m(t,T)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\nu_{i}(t,T)\intop_{t}^{T}\nu_{i}(t,s)\; ds
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multi-Factor Musiela Parametrization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\overline{f}(t,\tau)=\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,\tau)\intop_{t}^{T}\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,s)\; ds+\frac{\partial\overline{f}(t,\tau)}{\partial\tau}\right)dt+\sum_{i=1}^{k}\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,\tau)dX_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

